“\section{Method}
\subsection{Preference Approximation (PA) algorithm.}
Similar with Online DPO, the PA algorithm also deploys training of LLMs on $\mathcal{D}_{\theta}$. Differently, the PA algorithm uses the following loss function based on the KL divergence:
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
&\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{PA}}(\pi_\theta; \pi_{\text {ref }}) \\
=&\mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D},y_1,y_2\sim \pi_\theta(y|x)}\left[\mathrm{KL}(p^*(z|y_1,y_2,x)||p_\theta(z|y_1,y_2,x))\right]\\
=&\mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D},y_1,y_2\sim \pi_\theta(y|x)}\left[\mathrm{H}(p^*(z|y_1,y_2,x)||p_\theta(z|y_1,y_2,x))\right]\\
&+\mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D},y_1,y_2\sim \pi_\theta(y|x)}\left[M(x,y_1,y_2)\right],
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
where $M(x,y_1,y_2)=\sum_{z=0,1}p^*(z|y_1,y_2,x)\log p^*(z|y_1,y_2,x)$. In section \ref{PBA_sec}, we will demonstrate that the PA algorithm and the PPO algorithm share the same target distribution. In contrast, Online DPO lacks such theoretical support, despite the fact that DPO is derived from PPO.
We propose the Trust Region Preference Approximation (TRPA) algorithm for stable RL training, which leverages the technical routes of rule-based and preference-based optimization.
\subsection{Trust Region Preference Approximation (TRPA)}
Trust Region Preference Approximation (TRPA) is a preference-based optimization method based on the rule-based optimization scheme. See Figure \ref{ROROPO_TRPA} for the training process of TRPA. The TRPA algorithm utilizes a predefined rule to classify the multiple responses generated by LLM into different preference levels. The preference level represents the degree to which the corresponding response is preferred based on our predefined rule. Then we construct preference pairs between responses which have the same prompt but different preference levels. Finally, these preference pairs are used for optimization under the loss function of the TRPA algorithm. Given the reference policy $\pi_{ref}(y|x)$ and the policy $\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}$ which is the policy before the current optimization step and used for generating data $\mathcal{D}_{\text{old}}$, the TRPA algorithm trains the policy model $\pi_{\theta}$ under the following loss function:
\begin{equation}\label{TRPRA_eq}
\small{\begin{aligned}
&\mathcal{L}_{\text{TRPA}}\left(\pi_{\theta};\pi_{\text {ref }}\right)=-\mathbb{E}_{\left(x, y_1, y_2\right) \sim \mathcal{D}_{\text{old}}}\left[\log \sigma\left(\bar{h}_{\theta}\left(x, y_1, y_2\right)\right)\right]\\
&\quad\quad\quad\quad+\lambda\mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D}}\left[{\mathrm{D}_{\mathrm{KL}}(\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\cdot|x)||\pi_{\theta}(\cdot|x))}\right],
\end{aligned}}
\end{equation}
where $\bar{h}_{\theta}\left(x, y_1, y_2\right)=\beta(y_1) \log \frac{\pi_\theta\left(y_1 \mid x\right)}{\pi_{\text {ref }}\left(y_1 \mid x\right)}-\beta(y_1) \log \frac{\pi_\theta\left(y_2 \mid x\right)}{\pi_{\text {ref }}\left(y_2 \mid x\right)}$, $\mathcal{D}_{\text{old}}\triangleq \{(x,y_1,y_2)|x\sim\mathcal{D},y_1,y_2\sim\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\cdot|x),(y_1\succ y_2)\sim p^*(1|y_1,y_2,x)\}$, $\lambda$ is a hyper-parameter and $\beta(y_1)$ is the KTPO coefficient which will be discussed in Section \ref{TRPA_details}.\ding{194}.
\subsection{Technical Details}\label{TRPA_details}
Building on the principles of preference-based optimization, we develop several key techniques tailored to the TRPA framework to support more effective reasoning and planning in LLMs.
\ding{192} \textbf{KL Regularization.} Maintaining controlled update steps facilitates smoother convergence during training. TRPA incorporates the constraint
${\mathrm{D}_{\mathrm{KL}}(\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\cdot|x)||\pi_{\theta}(\cdot|x))}$ to effectively leverage the benefits of trust region principle. By limiting the KL divergence between successive policies, TRPA ensures gradual updates, thereby preventing abrupt changes that could destabilize the training process.
\ding{193} \textbf{Definition of Rule and Preference Levels.} We adopt the same reward categorization rule as the rule-based optimization algorithms, such as Logic RL \cite{xie2025logic} and DeepScaleR \cite{deepscaler2025}. Specifically, we define four preference levels to evaluate LLM-generated responses, ranging from Level 4 (lowest) to Level 1 (highest), based on both formatting and factual correctness. %The quality of responses from preference level 4 to 1 gradually increases.
\begin{tcolorbox}[
    colframe=color_pl,
    colback=blue!5!white,
    coltitle=white, % 标题文字颜色：白色
    fonttitle=\bfseries, % 标题字体加粗
    title=Preference Levels\label{Preference_Levels}, % 标题内容
    arc=3mm, % 设置角弧度，使其成为钝角
    boxrule=0.5mm, % 边框宽度
    % drop fuzzy shadow=gray!30 % 添加柔和阴影
]
$\bullet$ Preference Level 4: Responses that violate basic formatting requirements. Specifically, we require responses to follow the standard Chain-of-Thought (CoT) format: the reasoning process and final answer must be enclosed in \texttt{<think>...</think>} and \texttt{<answer>...</answer>} tags, respectively. For math-related problems, the final answer should be wrapped in \texttt{\textbackslash\textbackslash boxed\{\}}.\\
$\bullet$ Preference Level 3: Responses that meet formatting requirements but exhibit incomplete or illogical reasoning, indicating a partial understanding of the expected format. \\
$\bullet$ Preference Level 2: Responses that are correctly formatted but still contain factual error. \\
$\bullet$ Preference Level 1: Responses that are both well-formatted and factually correct.
\end{tcolorbox}
Here we explain why we choose the BT model \cite{bradley1952rank} instead of listwise ranking models (e.g. \cite{luce1959individual}). In our experiments, we observe that rollouts under the same prompt typically yield outputs falling into two adjacent preference levels, supporting the assumption of binary comparisons of the BT model.
\ding{194} \textbf{Kahneman-Tversky Preference Optimization (KTPO).} To better guide the optimization process, we introduce the KTPO technique, inspired by Prospect Theory (Kahneman–Tversky model) \cite{altman2010prospect}, which suggests that humans exhibit asymmetric sensitivity to gains and losses. Motivated by this asymmetry, we design the hyperparameter $\beta(y)$ to be anisotropic, assigning larger values when $y$ corresponds to a response of higher preference level (e.g., Level 1). Let $\beta$ be the base hyperparameter and $N$ be the Kahneman–Tversky factor, then
\begin{equation}
    \beta(y) =
\begin{cases}
N\cdot\beta, & \text{if } y \text{ belongs to Preference Level 1}, \\
\beta, & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}
% Due to space limitations, this paper does not further explore the specific implementation of more $\beta$ parameter adjustment methods.
The design of KTPO is inspired by Kahneman \& Tversky’s prospect theory, which explains that humans tend to be more sensitive to relative losses than to relative gains of the same magnitude. KTPO aims to amplify the weight of positive (i.e., higher-preference) data during the learning process, encouraging the model to focus more on relative gains. This allows the LLM to learn high-preference-level responses more effectively, thereby accelerating the overall training process.
TRPA introduces the adaptive hyperparameter $\beta$ (i.e. KTPO) for the first time in the LLMs Reasoning tasks. Experimental results show that this method can significantly improve model performance. It is worth noting that in the Human Alignment tasks, there are a series of preference optimization algorithms (such as WPO \cite{zhou2024wpo}, Adaptive DPO \cite{hong2024adaptive}, NS-DPO \cite{son2024right}, $\beta$-DPO \cite{wu2024beta}, KTO \cite{KTO}, etc.) that follow the idea of anisotropy to improve the algorithm performance through the design of $\beta$. Given the focus of this study, we did not conduct a detailed horizontal comparison of existing methods, but their ideas have certain commonalities with this study.
\ding{195} \textbf{Prompt-wised Optimization Strategy.} In both the early and late stages of optimization, LLMs often generate responses with identical preference levels (or function values) under the same prompt. This typically arises from undertraining in the early phase and overtraining or convergence in the later phase. For example, in GRPO \cite{shao2024deepseekmath}, this phenomenon leads to normalized rewards being zero, which in turn causes the gradient of the loss function to vanish, rendering the optimization ineffective. In contrast, the TRPA algorithm naturally accommodates such scenarios through a Prompt-wised Optimization Strategy: when all responses have a preference level of 1, they are treated as $y_1$ and the corresponding $y_2$ terms are omitted during optimization; conversely, when all responses share a non-1 but identical preference level, they are treated as $y_2$, and the $y_1$ terms are excluded accordingly.“上述内容是我的文章的方法部分，请你按照“偏好优化方法DPO作为LLM领域中一类经典算法却在learning-to-resoning任务上表现不好（例如OnlineDPO方法）。我们发现理论上偏好优化方法在learning-to-resoning这类在线优化任务下存在理论缺陷。因此我们提出了修正的在线偏好优化方法PA算法，并同时设计了一类松弛方法TRPA方法进行高效计算”的大逻辑进行适当的修改，使这一部分的内容合理、通顺。

