\section{Method}
\subsection{Motivation: Why DPO-style preference optimization struggles in learning-to-reasoning}
Preference optimization methods such as DPO have become a standard paradigm for aligning LLMs. However, in \emph{learning-to-reasoning} tasks, training is typically conducted in an \emph{online} manner: the model continually generates new rollouts, and the optimization target evolves with the current policy. Empirically, DPO-style online variants (e.g., Online DPO) often underperform on such tasks.

We attribute this to a theoretical mismatch: DPO is derived under assumptions that are better suited to \emph{offline} preference data (or fixed data distributions), while in online reasoning optimization the training distribution depends on the current policy. As a result, directly applying DPO to $\mathcal{D}_{\theta}$ lacks a clear guarantee that it optimizes the same target distribution as trust-region RL methods (e.g., PPO), which are known to be stable in online settings.

To address this issue, we (i) propose a corrected online preference optimization method, \textbf{Preference Approximation (PA)}, which is theoretically consistent with the target distribution optimized by PPO; and (ii) further develop a computationally efficient and stable \textbf{Trust Region Preference Approximation (TRPA)} method by combining rule-based preference construction with trust-region regularization.

\subsection{Preference Approximation (PA) algorithm}
Similar to Online DPO, PA also performs online training on the on-policy dataset $\mathcal{D}_{\theta}$. The key difference is that PA is derived from directly approximating the \emph{true preference posterior} with a model-induced posterior under KL divergence, rather than adopting the DPO surrogate that may become inconsistent under online data collection.

Formally, PA minimizes the following KL-based objective:
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\mathrm{PA}}(\pi_\theta; \pi_{\text {ref }})
=&\mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D},y_1,y_2\sim \pi_\theta(y|x)}\left[\mathrm{KL}(p^*(z|y_1,y_2,x)\Vert p_\theta(z|y_1,y_2,x))\right]\\
=&\mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D},y_1,y_2\sim \pi_\theta(y|x)}\left[\mathrm{H}(p^*(z|y_1,y_2,x), p_\theta(z|y_1,y_2,x))\right]\\
&+\mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D},y_1,y_2\sim \pi_\theta(y|x)}\left[M(x,y_1,y_2)\right],
\end{aligned}
\end{equation}
where $M(x,y_1,y_2)=\sum_{z=0,1}p^*(z|y_1,y_2,x)\log p^*(z|y_1,y_2,x)$ is independent of $\theta$.

In Section~\ref{PBA_sec}, we show that PA shares the \emph{same target distribution} as PPO under the online optimization setting, providing theoretical support that is missing for Online DPO. This makes PA a theoretically corrected preference-optimization alternative for learning-to-reasoning tasks.

\subsection{From PA to an efficient relaxed method: Trust Region Preference Approximation (TRPA)}
Although PA provides a theoretically consistent objective, practical learning-to-reasoning training typically requires (1) stable updates under online rollouts, and (2) scalable preference supervision. To this end, we introduce a relaxed and efficient variant, \textbf{Trust Region Preference Approximation (TRPA)}.

TRPA follows a rule-based optimization route to construct preferences efficiently: for each prompt, the LLM generates multiple responses; a predefined rule assigns each response a \emph{preference level}; we then form preference pairs from responses with the same prompt but different levels, and optimize the policy using a preference loss with a trust-region constraint to ensure stability. The training process is shown in Figure~\ref{ROROPO_TRPA}.

Given a reference policy $\pi_{\text{ref}}(y|x)$ and the behavior policy $\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}$ that generates on-policy data $\mathcal{D}_{\text{old}}$, TRPA optimizes $\pi_\theta$ with:
\begin{equation}\label{TRPRA_eq}
\small{
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}_{\text{TRPA}}\left(\pi_{\theta};\pi_{\text {ref }}\right)
=&-\mathbb{E}_{\left(x, y_1, y_2\right) \sim \mathcal{D}_{\text{old}}}\left[\log \sigma\left(\bar{h}_{\theta}\left(x, y_1, y_2\right)\right)\right]\\
&\quad+\lambda\mathbb{E}_{x\sim \mathcal{D}}\left[{\mathrm{D}_{\mathrm{KL}}(\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\cdot|x)\Vert\pi_{\theta}(\cdot|x))}\right],
\end{aligned}}
\end{equation}
where
\[
\bar{h}_{\theta}\left(x, y_1, y_2\right)
=\beta(y_1)\log \frac{\pi_\theta\left(y_1 \mid x\right)}{\pi_{\text {ref }}\left(y_1 \mid x\right)}
-\beta(y_1)\log \frac{\pi_\theta\left(y_2 \mid x\right)}{\pi_{\text {ref }}\left(y_2 \mid x\right)},
\]
\[
\mathcal{D}_{\text{old}}\triangleq \{(x,y_1,y_2)\mid x\sim\mathcal{D},\,y_1,y_2\sim\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\cdot|x),\,(y_1\succ y_2)\sim p^*(1|y_1,y_2,x)\},
\]
$\lambda$ is a hyper-parameter, and $\beta(\cdot)$ is the KTPO coefficient introduced in Section~\ref{TRPA_details}.

\subsection{Technical Details}\label{TRPA_details}
Building on preference-based optimization, we design several techniques to make TRPA stable and effective for online reasoning optimization.

\paragraph{\ding{192} KL Regularization (Trust Region).}
Online optimization is prone to instability when policy updates are too aggressive. TRPA incorporates the trust-region term
$\mathrm{D}_{\mathrm{KL}}(\pi_{\theta_{\text{old}}}(\cdot|x)\Vert\pi_{\theta}(\cdot|x))$
to constrain the update magnitude, promoting smooth improvements and preventing collapse.

\paragraph{\ding{193} Rule definition and preference levels.}
We adopt the same reward categorization rule used in rule-based optimization methods (e.g., Logic RL~\cite{xie2025logic} and DeepScaleR~\cite{deepscaler2025}). We define four preference levels (Level 4 lowest to Level 1 highest) based on formatting and correctness:
\begin{tcolorbox}[
    colframe=color_pl,
    colback=blue!5!white,
    coltitle=white,
    fonttitle=\bfseries,
    title=Preference Levels\label{Preference_Levels},
    arc=3mm,
    boxrule=0.5mm
]
$\bullet$ Preference Level 4: Violates basic formatting. We require standard CoT format: reasoning and final answer must be enclosed in \texttt{
<details type="reasoning" done="true" duration="0">
<summary>Thought for 0 seconds</summary>
&gt; ...
</details>
} and \texttt{<answer>...</answer>} tags; for math problems, final answers should be wrapped in \texttt{\textbackslash boxed\{\}}.\\
$\bullet$ Preference Level 3: Correct format but incomplete/illogical reasoning.\\
$\bullet$ Preference Level 2: Correct format but factually incorrect.\\
$\bullet$ Preference Level 1: Correct format and factually correct.
\end{tcolorbox}

We use the Bradley--Terry (BT) model~\cite{bradley1952rank} instead of listwise ranking (e.g.,~\cite{luce1959individual}), because in practice rollouts under the same prompt usually fall into two adjacent preference levels, making pairwise comparisons a suitable approximation.

\paragraph{\ding{194} Kahneman--Tversky Preference Optimization (KTPO).}
To emphasize learning from high-quality responses, we introduce an anisotropic coefficient $\beta(y)$ inspired by prospect theory~\cite{altman2010prospect}. Let $\beta$ be a base hyperparameter and $N$ be a Kahneman--Tversky factor:
\begin{equation}
\beta(y)=
\begin{cases}
N\cdot\beta, & \text{if } y \text{ is Preference Level 1},\\
\beta, & \text{otherwise}.
\end{cases}
\end{equation}
KTPO increases the effective learning signal from high-preference samples, improving optimization efficiency on reasoning tasks. We note that anisotropic $\beta$ designs have also been explored in human-alignment settings (e.g., WPO~\cite{zhou2024wpo}, Adaptive DPO~\cite{hong2024adaptive}, NS-DPO~\cite{son2024right}, $\beta$-DPO~\cite{wu2024beta}, KTO~\cite{KTO}); our work introduces this idea into online learning-to-reasoning via TRPA.

\paragraph{\ding{195} Prompt-wised Optimization Strategy.}
In online training, it is common that all rollouts under the same prompt share the same preference level: in early stages due to undertraining, and in late stages due to convergence/overtraining. Such cases can lead to vanishing gradients in methods relying on normalized rewards (e.g., GRPO~\cite{shao2024deepseekmath}). TRPA naturally handles this by a prompt-wise strategy:
(i) if all responses are Level 1, we treat them as $y_1$ and omit the $y_2$ term; 
(ii) if all responses share the same non-1 level, we treat them as $y_2$ and omit the $y_1$ term.
This prevents the optimization signal from collapsing when pairwise contrast is unavailable within a prompt.
